tool_input.plan:
# Plan: Add `mistral-instruct-v3` Chat Template Handler

## Context

Mistral Instruct v0.3 uses a distinct chat format:
- User turns wrapped with `[INST] … [/INST]`
- System messages prepended (inline) to the first user turn, separated by `\n\n`
- Assistant turns terminated with `</s>`
- **No** `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` wrapper (unlike Ministral 3 / Mistral Large v7)

The existing specialized-template dispatcher in `common/chat.cpp` already handles
Ministral 3 (which requires `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`). We need to add a new handler that
catches templates which have `[INST]` but **lack** `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`, bypassing the
autoparser (which can misbehave on bracket-style Mistral formats) and using the
simpler `CONTENT_ONLY` output format.

**Constraints:**
- Do **not** touch `src/llama-chat.h` (the enum header)
- Do **not** modify any existing handler function or detection block
- Add new code only — one file: `common/chat.cpp`

---

## Critical Files

| File | Role |
|------|------|
| `common/chat.cpp` | **Only file to edit.** Add the new handler function and one detection clause. |
| `src/llama-chat.h` | Defines `llm_chat_template` enum — **do not modify** |
| `src/llama-chat.cpp` | Legacy string-map + heuristic detection — **do not modify** |
| `common/chat.h` | Declares `common_chat_try_specialized_template` — **do not modify** |

---

## Implementation Steps

### Step 1 — Add the handler function in `common/chat.cpp`

**Where:** Insert after line 940 (end of `common_chat_params_init_ministral_3`)
and before `common_chat_params_init_gpt_oss` at line 942.

**What:** A new static function that:
1. Scans `inputs.messages` and accumulates any `"system"` role content.
2. On the **first** `"user"` message, prepends the collected system prompt (with `\n\n` separator) into the message's `"content"` field.
3. Passes the adjusted messages to the existing
   `common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl()` utility (so BOS/EOS tokens from
   the GGUF Jinja template are still handled).
4. Sets `data.format = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY` — no PEG parser needed
   for this simple non-reasoning, non-tool format.

```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    // Mistral Instruct v0.3 format:
    //   [INST] {system}\n\n{user} [/INST]{assistant}</s>...
    // System messages are prepended to the first user turn; no [SYSTEM_PROMPT] wrapper.
    // See: https://huggingface.co/mistralai/Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3
    common_chat_params data;

    auto adjusted_messages = json::array();
    std::string system_prompt;
    bool first_user_seen = false;

    for (const auto & msg : inputs.messages) {
        const auto role = msg.value("role", "");
        if (role == "system") {
            system_prompt += msg.value("content", "");
            continue;
        }
        if (!first_user_seen && role == "user" && !system_prompt.empty()) {
            auto adjusted = msg;
            adjusted["content"] = system_prompt + "\n\n" + msg.value("content", "");
            adjusted_messages.push_back(adjusted);
            first_user_seen = true;
            continue;
        }
        first_user_seen = true;
        adjusted_messages.push_back(msg);
    }

    data.prompt = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(
        tmpl, inputs, /* messages_override = */ adjusted_messages);
    data.format = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY;
    return data;
}
```

### Step 2 — Register detection in `common_chat_try_specialized_template()`

**Where:** In `common_chat_try_specialized_template()` (starts at line 1634),
append a new `if` block **after** the Ministral 3 block (lines 1638–1644) and
**before** the GPT-OSS block.

**Detection logic:** Template contains `[INST]` (Mistral-style) but does **not**
contain `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` (distinguishes from Ministral 3 / Mistral Large v7,
both of which do contain `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`).

```cpp
    // Mistral Instruct v0.3 — uses [INST]/[/INST] markers with system prepended
    // to the first user turn; no [SYSTEM_PROMPT] wrapper (unlike Ministral 3).
    if (src.find("[INST]") != std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos) {
        LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: mistral-instruct-v3\n");
        return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
    }
```

---

## Reused Utilities

| Symbol | File | Purpose |
|--------|------|---------|
| `common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl()` | `common/chat.cpp` (line 767) | Applies the Jinja template with optional message override; handles BOS/EOS stripping |
| `COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY` | `common/chat.h` (line 148) | Signals that model output is plain content, no PEG parsing needed |
| `json::array()` / `nlohmann::ordered_json` | already included | Message list construction |
| `LOG_DBG` | already included | Debug logging (matches pattern of all other handlers) |

---

## Verification

1. **Build:** `cmake --build build -j $(nproc)` — should compile with no new warnings.
2. **Legacy path smoke test** (checks that existing `llm_chat_detect_template` is unaffected):
   ```
   echo '[{"role":"user","content":"Hello"}]' | \
     ./build/bin/llama-cli --chat-template mistral-v3 ...
   ```
3. **Jinja/specialized path test** — supply an actual Mistral Instruct v0.3 GGUF
   (or mock the `.jinja` template) and confirm:
   - System message is merged into the first `[INST]` turn.
   - No `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` wrapper appears in the output.
   - `[INST] … [/INST]` brackets appear around user content.
   - `</s>` appears after assistant content.
4. **Ministral 3 regression:** Verify that a Ministral/Ministral-Large model (whose
   Jinja template contains `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`) still routes to the Ministral 3 handler,
   not the new one.
5. **Existing test suite:**
   ```
   ./build/bin/test-chat-template
   ./build/bin/test-chat
   ```
   Both should pass without regressions.

